00:00:01.430 --> 00:00:05.141
Prof: What I'd like to
do this morning is spend eight

00:00:05.141 --> 00:00:09.103
or ten minutes with a few slides
that are framing and background

00:00:09.103 --> 00:00:10.110
to the case.
 

00:00:10.110 --> 00:00:17.330
And then I'm going to ask Nancy
Hite to impersonate Sharon

00:00:17.330 --> 00:00:20.710
Oster,
with the flying chalk on the

00:00:20.710 --> 00:00:23.042
board,
and I'm going to come around

00:00:23.042 --> 00:00:25.400
and talk to all of you about the
case.

00:00:25.400 --> 00:00:29.070
And we'll work it through B
school style.

00:00:29.070 --> 00:00:35.625
When you look at the
institutions involved in the

00:00:35.625 --> 00:00:41.524
mortgage system,
don't assume that they were

00:00:41.524 --> 00:00:47.357
designed brilliantly,
or that they were thought out

00:00:47.357 --> 00:00:49.750
from beginning to end.
 

00:00:49.750 --> 00:00:52.131
The concept of
"kluge,"

00:00:52.131 --> 00:00:54.290
is that in your vocabulary?
 

00:00:54.290 --> 00:00:56.310
Tim, is that,
"kluge,"

00:00:56.310 --> 00:00:58.917
is that a-- hands up if
"kluge"

00:00:58.917 --> 00:00:59.960
is familiar.
 

00:00:59.960 --> 00:01:03.899
I'm not going to get anywhere
with that idea.

00:01:03.899 --> 00:01:07.311
"Kluge"
means things that are complex

00:01:07.311 --> 00:01:08.870
and badly designed.
 

00:01:08.870 --> 00:01:15.061
And there's a wonderful book by
Gary Marcus called Kluge,

00:01:15.061 --> 00:01:19.156
which is about badly
designed stuff,

00:01:19.156 --> 00:01:24.590
from economic institutions;
to human memory;

00:01:24.590 --> 00:01:32.010
to the human spine,
which is a highly error-prone

00:01:32.010 --> 00:01:37.670
structure,
and is as it is not

00:01:37.670 --> 00:01:43.393
because evolution said,
"What's the very best

00:01:43.393 --> 00:01:48.160
support column I can make for a
bipedal creature?"

00:01:48.160 --> 00:01:52.242
but, "What's the best I
can do by evolving from a

00:01:52.242 --> 00:01:55.709
four-legged to a two-legged
creature?"

00:01:55.709 --> 00:02:00.978
And the spine shows all kinds
of design imperfections that are

00:02:00.978 --> 00:02:06.248
attributable to the fact that it
evolved in a horizontal plain

00:02:06.248 --> 00:02:10.310
and then was readapted in a
vertical plain.

00:02:10.310 --> 00:02:16.419
And the institutions at play
in, what Posner calls the

00:02:16.419 --> 00:02:22.002
Depression of '08,
and what most of us call the

00:02:22.002 --> 00:02:25.504
Recession of 08/'09,
though it is,

00:02:25.504 --> 00:02:28.628
perhaps, the mother of all
recessions,

00:02:28.628 --> 00:02:34.579
it has not actually obtained
the depth of unemployment and

00:02:34.579 --> 00:02:40.738
under-utilization of plant and
equipment that would match up

00:02:40.738 --> 00:02:43.870
with the one in the 1930s.
 

00:02:43.870 --> 00:02:45.310
Of course, we could still get
there.

00:02:45.310 --> 00:02:55.485
It is possible that it is now
1931 and another dip is out

00:02:55.485 --> 00:02:56.940
there.
 

00:02:56.940 --> 00:03:00.449
I don't think that but there
are those, including Will

00:03:00.449 --> 00:03:04.687
Goetzmann, who we saw a few days
ago, who speculate that it might

00:03:04.687 --> 00:03:05.348
be so.
 

00:03:05.348 --> 00:03:15.639
This is a cast of characters
for subprime lending;

00:03:15.639 --> 00:03:18.712
left to right:
the homebuyer,

00:03:18.712 --> 00:03:20.810
the broker,
the appraiser,

00:03:20.810 --> 00:03:23.712
the mortgage lender,
the investment banker and the

00:03:23.712 --> 00:03:27.620
investors in the bonds created
by the investment banks.

00:03:27.620 --> 00:03:35.854
And in the row I'm touching are
the principal incentives that

00:03:35.854 --> 00:03:39.560
make the whole system go.
 

00:03:39.560 --> 00:03:47.520
And the critical thing is that
three,

00:03:47.520 --> 00:03:50.565
and arguably four,
of the main steps in the

00:03:50.565 --> 00:03:56.717
process are fee-driven,
so that the alignment between

00:03:56.717 --> 00:04:02.310
the decision maker and the
investor,

00:04:02.310 --> 00:04:08.020
or between the decision maker
and the potential home buyer,

00:04:08.020 --> 00:04:14.318
may be muted by the decision
maker thinking "fees."

00:04:14.318 --> 00:04:20.428
If I'm thinking--let's suppose
I were a college admissions

00:04:20.428 --> 00:04:26.752
officer and I was paid by the
live students delivered to the

00:04:26.752 --> 00:04:31.620
school,
I might become very generous in

00:04:31.620 --> 00:04:34.848
my view;
I might find creativity in

00:04:34.848 --> 00:04:38.476
unexpected places;
I might imagine analytic

00:04:38.476 --> 00:04:41.009
firepower where none existed.
 

00:04:41.009 --> 00:04:45.495
And so, in all these steps,
the bias toward

00:04:45.495 --> 00:04:50.194
"yes,"
the bias toward completing a

00:04:50.194 --> 00:04:56.634
transaction,
is a very powerful piece of the

00:04:56.634 --> 00:04:57.680
story.
 

00:04:57.680 --> 00:05:00.269
