00:19:50.233 --> 00:19:51.883
Douglas W. Rae:
That's the trouble with

00:19:51.883 --> 00:19:54.519
letting me learn your name;
you get cold called.

00:19:54.519 --> 00:19:59.944
There's a story in this where a
local broker ends up being

00:19:59.944 --> 00:20:02.038
sentenced to prison.
 

00:20:02.038 --> 00:20:03.859
Do you remember that part of it
or not?

00:20:03.859 --> 00:20:05.759
Student: Mark.
 

00:20:05.759 --> 00:20:07.940
Prof: Okay, Mark.
 

00:20:07.940 --> 00:20:09.318
Can you give us a little recap
on Mark?

00:20:09.318 --> 00:20:12.525
Student:
Mark Kellogg submitted

00:20:12.525 --> 00:20:16.250
fraudulent data for about
seventy homes,

00:20:16.250 --> 00:20:19.940
and--or somehow ended up,
I'm not sure of the process of

00:20:19.940 --> 00:20:24.085
flipping a house exactly,
but he did it to seventy homes

00:20:24.085 --> 00:20:27.710
and they all ended up defaulting
on the loans,

00:20:27.710 --> 00:20:29.838
the people that he sold it to.
 

00:20:29.838 --> 00:20:33.660
Prof: Okay,
so Mark's sin would be what?

00:20:33.660 --> 00:20:36.788
Let's try somebody else.
 

00:20:36.788 --> 00:20:42.375
What's Mark--if Mark were a
relative of yours and you had to

00:20:42.375 --> 00:20:47.770
have Thanksgiving dinner with
him while he was on furlough

00:20:47.770 --> 00:20:54.313
from Ohio State Penitentiary,
what topic would you want it to

00:20:54.313 --> 00:21:01.990
reflect on;
ethical topic?

00:21:01.990 --> 00:21:09.278
You want to take a shot at this?
 

00:21:09.278 --> 00:21:13.532
Student:
Perhaps, as you just mentioned

00:21:13.532 --> 00:21:17.220
with the topic of preying on
zebras,

00:21:17.220 --> 00:21:21.278
perhaps something like that,
and that--

00:21:21.278 --> 00:21:27.519
using a position to benefit
from people at a much

00:21:27.519 --> 00:21:31.028
&gt;
 

00:21:31.028 --> 00:21:33.480
than you, and to their
detriment and to your gain.

00:21:33.480 --> 00:21:33.890
Prof: Okay.
 

00:21:33.890 --> 00:21:35.690
So the buyers,
on your telling,

00:21:35.690 --> 00:21:36.470
are zebras.
 

00:21:36.470 --> 00:21:43.259
Okay, that's a plausible
position.

00:21:43.259 --> 00:21:48.012
If the buyers are zebras,
are the zebras in any way

00:21:48.012 --> 00:21:50.390
blamable in this story?
 

00:21:50.390 --> 00:21:56.009
What do you think?
 

00:21:56.009 --> 00:21:59.228
Student:
It's possible that they're

00:21:59.228 --> 00:22:02.140
blamable,
if they were given good

00:22:02.140 --> 00:22:04.704
information,
but in this situation they were

00:22:04.704 --> 00:22:07.127
given completely wrongful
information and led to believe

00:22:07.127 --> 00:22:08.009
that it was true.
 

00:22:08.009 --> 00:22:10.019
Prof: Okay.
 

00:22:10.019 --> 00:22:11.932
Student:
Like, a plausible person would

00:22:11.932 --> 00:22:12.568
believe that.
 

00:22:12.568 --> 00:22:16.999
Prof: Can we tell a
story where it's plausible to

00:22:16.999 --> 00:22:18.529
blame the buyers?
 

00:22:18.529 --> 00:22:20.470
Student: Yes.
 

00:22:20.470 --> 00:22:25.141
Where they should have known
that they don't have the income

00:22:25.141 --> 00:22:29.098
to pay the loan and they were
going to default,

00:22:29.098 --> 00:22:32.420
and so therefore they should
have not bought the home.

00:22:32.420 --> 00:22:33.970
Prof: Thank you.
 

00:22:33.970 --> 00:22:39.127
And are their instances where
people are encouraged to lie

00:22:39.127 --> 00:22:41.118
about their incomes?
 

00:22:41.118 --> 00:22:44.442
Student:
I think there's a big problem

00:22:44.442 --> 00:22:48.597
with a lot of these "Jumbo
Subprime Mortgages"

00:22:48.597 --> 00:22:51.618
they called them,
where people were buying really

00:22:51.618 --> 00:22:53.046
big houses,
or second houses,

00:22:53.046 --> 00:22:56.118
with subprime mortgages and in
that case it is their fault,

00:22:56.118 --> 00:22:57.710
because they were just being
greedy,

00:22:57.710 --> 00:22:58.848
right.
 

00:22:58.848 --> 00:23:01.971
And trying to take--trying to
either falsify documents or go

00:23:01.971 --> 00:23:05.250
for the type of loans that would
allow them to get these second

00:23:05.250 --> 00:23:08.319
properties without really having
enough to back it up.

00:23:08.319 --> 00:23:10.890
Prof: Okay.
 

00:23:10.890 --> 00:23:15.695
So, that's the sin of pride or
gluttony, not really gluttony,

00:23:15.695 --> 00:23:18.740
but it's bricks and mortar
gluttony.

00:23:18.740 --> 00:23:21.250
Yes?
 

00:23:21.250 --> 00:23:24.259
Student:
Well there were also NINJA

00:23:24.259 --> 00:23:26.390
loans,
which I think is a very

00:23:26.390 --> 00:23:29.460
appropriate acronym because of
the sneakiness,

00:23:29.460 --> 00:23:31.799
but it was an acronym for no
income,

00:23:31.799 --> 00:23:33.170
no job and no assets.
 

00:23:33.170 --> 00:23:34.358
Professor Douglas W.
 

00:23:34.358 --> 00:23:35.776
Rae: Okay,
NINJA: No Income,

00:23:35.776 --> 00:23:36.690
No Job, No Assets.
 

00:23:36.690 --> 00:23:44.679
And why would anyone encourage
another human being to seek a

00:23:44.679 --> 00:23:46.440
NINJA loan?
 

00:23:46.440 --> 00:23:48.920
Is it obvious?
 

00:23:48.920 --> 00:23:52.784
Student:
Well, if you're one of the

00:23:52.784 --> 00:23:57.779
three steps that profits off of
the fee of making--

00:23:57.779 --> 00:24:00.588
of having that loan go through,
then you don't even--

00:24:00.588 --> 00:24:02.028
it doesn't really matter to you
if it--

00:24:02.028 --> 00:24:04.957
or it doesn't matter to you if
it defaults as much as it

00:24:04.957 --> 00:24:06.980
matters to the buyer or to the
bank.

00:24:06.980 --> 00:24:08.470
Prof: Okay.
 

00:24:08.470 --> 00:24:11.912
So as long as you can
successfully pass it along to

00:24:11.912 --> 00:24:14.941
the next step,
you collect the fee and you're

00:24:14.941 --> 00:24:17.420
home-dry no matter what happens.
 

00:24:17.420 --> 00:24:18.926
Student:
Right, and your reputation

00:24:18.926 --> 00:24:19.920
&gt;
 

00:24:19.920 --> 00:24:20.179
..
 

00:24:20.179 --> 00:24:26.920
Prof: Okay now,
let's stop and see what we got

00:24:26.920 --> 00:24:30.940
for a diagram here,
Sharon.

00:24:30.940 --> 00:24:33.930
Student:
&gt;

00:24:33.930 --> 00:24:36.000
Prof: Unpack your
diagram.

00:24:36.000 --> 00:24:37.048
Student:
Okay, so I guess this is...

00:24:37.048 --> 00:24:38.640
Prof: I knew you'd be
good at diagrams.

00:24:38.640 --> 00:24:40.710
Student:
Our game of Pictionary.

00:24:40.710 --> 00:24:44.130
So, I'm trying to map out what
exactly went wrong,

00:24:44.130 --> 00:24:48.519
and I would start with a home
in the Slavic community and then

00:24:48.519 --> 00:24:50.714
I would end,
maybe, here with Bank of

00:24:50.714 --> 00:24:51.180
Scotland.
 

00:24:51.180 --> 00:24:58.643
And between "Joe six
pack" purchasing a home

00:24:58.643 --> 00:25:05.612
with a $22,000 yearly income,
which was the average I saw,

00:25:05.612 --> 00:25:10.536
that was misrepresented as
being worth about $80,000 from

00:25:10.536 --> 00:25:15.827
the broker who works with a--
I figured we could have

00:25:15.827 --> 00:25:19.598
everyone fill in the parts for
me.

00:25:19.598 --> 00:25:23.685
Like, how do we get from the
home to the international

00:25:23.685 --> 00:25:24.380
crisis?
 

00:25:24.380 --> 00:25:30.278
Prof: Okay,
so who's &lt;&lt;technical

00:25:30.278 --> 00:25:32.288
chat&gt;&gt;.
 

00:25:32.288 --> 00:25:38.190
What's the next step in the
chain to the right of broker?

00:25:38.190 --> 00:25:41.913
Student:
Probably someone will give a

00:25:41.913 --> 00:25:46.934
rating for this mortgage so that
the broker will be able to

00:25:46.934 --> 00:25:52.044
package it with other mortgages
and sell it to an investment

00:25:52.044 --> 00:25:53.170
banker.
 

00:25:53.170 --> 00:25:55.330
Prof: Okay,
so there's a credit rating

00:25:55.330 --> 00:25:58.278
story, but there's also another
story that's closer to ground

00:25:58.278 --> 00:25:58.769
level.
 

00:25:58.769 --> 00:26:07.548
It concerns the house itself.
 

00:26:07.548 --> 00:26:10.136
Student:
Need an evaluation of the

00:26:10.136 --> 00:26:12.660
house, like, what the house
value is.

00:26:12.660 --> 00:26:14.160
Prof: Okay.
 

00:26:14.160 --> 00:26:18.971
And there's a saying in real
estate "appraise as

00:26:18.971 --> 00:26:20.730
instructed."
 

00:26:20.730 --> 00:26:30.461
And it's not altogether false
that whoever hires--think about

00:26:30.461 --> 00:26:33.220
the incentives.
 

00:26:33.220 --> 00:26:37.461
You're an appraiser,
and Paul here hires you to do

00:26:37.461 --> 00:26:42.654
an appraisal and you're going to
get a fee of 1,100 bucks for

00:26:42.654 --> 00:26:43.779
doing it.
 

00:26:43.779 --> 00:26:48.626
And Paul lets it be known that
he thinks this house really

00:26:48.626 --> 00:26:52.710
ought to be worth something
north of $200,000.

00:26:52.710 --> 00:26:56.470
And you go out in the field,
do the comparables and the

00:26:56.470 --> 00:26:58.558
number comes up at $140,000.
 

00:26:58.558 --> 00:27:04.240
Tim, what thought might cross
your mind if you were--I

00:27:04.240 --> 00:27:09.278
understand in your case it,
of course, wouldn't,

00:27:09.278 --> 00:27:11.960
but in, say,
my case?

00:27:11.960 --> 00:27:14.107
Student:
It might cross your mind to

00:27:14.107 --> 00:27:16.819
trust all and just go with the
$200,000 prediction.

00:27:16.819 --> 00:27:18.900
Prof: Okay.
 

00:27:18.900 --> 00:27:21.288
And the second step in the
reasoning is?

00:27:21.288 --> 00:27:24.009
Student:
No-one will ever know.

00:27:24.009 --> 00:27:27.372
Prof: No-one will ever
know and next time Paul goes to

00:27:27.372 --> 00:27:29.390
the Yellow Pages for an
appraisal?

00:27:29.390 --> 00:27:31.000
Student:
He'll come to you.

00:27:31.000 --> 00:27:33.279
Prof: He'll come to you
or he's more likely to.

00:27:33.279 --> 00:27:36.470
He's a damn sight less likely
to if you undercut his deal.

00:27:36.470 --> 00:27:39.963
I'll tell you a Yale story
about appraisals:

00:27:39.963 --> 00:27:44.758
when I was in city government
we leased High Street and Wall

00:27:44.758 --> 00:27:48.089
Street to Yale for ninety-nine
years;

00:27:48.089 --> 00:27:50.348
we were broke, we needed money.
 

00:27:50.348 --> 00:27:57.299
And the Mayor sat down with
Benno Schmidt,

00:27:57.299 --> 00:28:01.945
and Benno said, "Well,
the University will handle the

00:28:01.945 --> 00:28:04.578
appraisal for you,"
and they did.

00:28:04.578 --> 00:28:08.275
The two streets together leased
for one million dollars for

00:28:08.275 --> 00:28:09.548
ninety-nine years.
 

00:28:09.548 --> 00:28:15.641
It should have been a lot more
than that and there were those,

00:28:15.641 --> 00:28:20.433
in city government,
who thought I was the guy who

00:28:20.433 --> 00:28:23.230
got the number that low.
 

00:28:23.230 --> 00:28:27.567
I was actually pulling hard on
making the number at least one

00:28:27.567 --> 00:28:30.098
zero or a zero-and-a-half
higher.

00:28:30.098 --> 00:28:33.474
I'd allow the Law School to
build that gorgeous underground

00:28:33.474 --> 00:28:36.910
library, because the ground
rights went with the streets.

00:28:36.910 --> 00:28:41.680
And so "appraise as
instructed"

00:28:41.680 --> 00:28:46.690
is an important component in
this story.

00:28:46.690 --> 00:28:51.250
We had the appraiser there.
 

00:28:51.250 --> 00:28:58.809
So, who else is involved and
what are their incentives?

00:28:58.809 --> 00:29:10.788
Paul?
 

00:29:10.788 --> 00:29:13.021
Student:
Well, you've got the local bank

00:29:13.021 --> 00:29:14.769
that's actually doing the
lending.

00:29:14.769 --> 00:29:16.328
Prof: Okay.
 

00:29:16.328 --> 00:29:19.092
Student:
And they probably will get a

00:29:19.092 --> 00:29:23.138
fee for the loan that they take
and then if they can package and

00:29:23.138 --> 00:29:26.961
sell it off to someone else,
they don't end up with the loan

00:29:26.961 --> 00:29:30.230
on their books so they couldn't,
probably, care less how it

00:29:30.230 --> 00:29:31.740
performs over the long run.
 

00:29:31.740 --> 00:29:32.910
Prof: Okay.
 

00:29:32.910 --> 00:29:37.417
So--terrific,
so, the lender is also

00:29:37.417 --> 00:29:45.145
fee-driven and is inclined to
think that she or he can escape

00:29:45.145 --> 00:29:51.200
accountability when the property
defaults,

00:29:51.200 --> 00:29:52.269
if it defaults.
 

00:29:52.269 --> 00:29:55.048
And why would that be?
 

00:29:55.048 --> 00:29:58.398
What are the--what do we turn
these loans into at the next

00:29:58.398 --> 00:29:58.868
stage?
 

00:29:58.868 --> 00:30:04.172
Student:
Usually it's sold off to a big

00:30:04.172 --> 00:30:11.358
investment bank or basically a
financial powerhouse where they

00:30:11.358 --> 00:30:16.190
pull the mortgages into these
giant,

00:30:16.190 --> 00:30:20.778
collateralized debt obligations
or &gt;

00:30:20.778 --> 00:30:23.009
Prof: Okay,
CDOs, famous acronym.

00:30:23.009 --> 00:30:24.529
Do you want to add anything to
this?

00:30:24.529 --> 00:30:24.779
Jaan Elias: Not really.
 

00:30:24.779 --> 00:30:25.618
Prof: Okay.
 

00:30:25.618 --> 00:30:30.808
So you've got the banks
creating these huge bundles,

00:30:30.808 --> 00:30:36.737
and the bundles--what story
could you tell to say that

00:30:36.737 --> 00:30:43.446
bundling these mortgages from
all across the country might be

00:30:43.446 --> 00:30:49.039
a good thing from the economy's
point of view.

00:30:49.039 --> 00:30:52.569
Is there anything you could say?
 

00:30:52.569 --> 00:30:56.960
 
 

00:30:56.960 --> 00:30:58.213
Student:
It diversifies the risk for

00:30:58.213 --> 00:30:59.170
those who are taking them out.
 

00:30:59.170 --> 00:31:00.160
Prof: Okay.
 

00:31:00.160 --> 00:31:02.578
It diversifies the risk,
say a little more.

00:31:02.578 --> 00:31:04.282
Student:
Well, presumably,

00:31:04.282 --> 00:31:07.528
the people who are packaging
them can take out a bunch of--

00:31:07.528 --> 00:31:11.974
do a lot of financial analysis
and determine that the risk of

00:31:11.974 --> 00:31:16.420
the number of defaults would be
lower than the benefit of the

00:31:16.420 --> 00:31:19.680
people actually paying their
loans back.

00:31:19.680 --> 00:31:22.721
So, the people who take out the
package would have a favorable

00:31:22.721 --> 00:31:23.420
risk return.
 

00:31:23.420 --> 00:31:24.868
Prof: Okay.
 

00:31:24.868 --> 00:31:26.720
And part--were you about to say
something?

00:31:26.720 --> 00:31:29.175
Student:
I think it also increase the

00:31:29.175 --> 00:31:31.553
market of potential buyers,
because now,

00:31:31.553 --> 00:31:34.593
rather than owning a mortgage
and having to deal with an

00:31:34.593 --> 00:31:37.154
investor one-on-one,
you have a pooling and

00:31:37.154 --> 00:31:40.243
servicing agreement that has a
company as a servicer who

00:31:40.243 --> 00:31:43.444
handles all the collection of
payments and distribution of

00:31:43.444 --> 00:31:45.579
money into different
investments.

00:31:45.579 --> 00:31:46.700
Prof: Okay.
 

00:31:46.700 --> 00:31:50.737
So, you've got an institutional
mechanism that makes this work

00:31:50.737 --> 00:31:55.473
relatively smoothly,
and you're interested,

00:31:55.473 --> 00:32:02.761
when you create these bundles,
in having the risks have

00:32:02.761 --> 00:32:07.660
relatively low correlation with
one another.

00:32:07.660 --> 00:32:13.695
What would be a bad bundle is
one where we can know that some

00:32:13.695 --> 00:32:19.230
of the mortgages are defaulting
and infer from that,

00:32:19.230 --> 00:32:22.088
that lots of others are likely
to default.

00:32:22.088 --> 00:32:25.640
And a bundle that was
geographically concentrated,

00:32:25.640 --> 00:32:29.316
on Slavic Village for example,
would have that second

00:32:29.316 --> 00:32:32.640
characteristic and that would be
a bad thing.

00:32:32.640 --> 00:32:41.548
So, there is a story about risk
management that makes that work.

00:32:41.548 --> 00:32:45.690
Now, are the agencies,
like Moody's,

00:32:45.690 --> 00:32:50.890
these outfits that judge
credit-worthiness of companies

00:32:50.890 --> 00:32:54.549
and other financial
intermediaries,

00:32:54.549 --> 00:32:56.548
are they in this story anywhere?
 

00:32:56.548 --> 00:32:59.790
I don't know if they--Jaan,
does Moody's get into your

00:32:59.790 --> 00:33:00.220
case?
 

00:33:00.220 --> 00:33:01.509
I don't think I found it.
 

00:33:01.509 --> 00:33:04.700
Jaan Elias:
Just as a kind of footnote.

00:33:04.700 --> 00:33:06.859
There are bating the CDOs.
 

00:33:06.859 --> 00:33:10.548
Prof: Okay.
 

00:33:10.548 --> 00:33:12.500
So, everybody know what Moody's
and its rivals do?

00:33:12.500 --> 00:33:36.490
Anybody want to help us with
that?

00:33:36.490 --> 00:33:37.990
Student:
Moody's and its rivals are--

00:33:37.990 --> 00:33:41.621
essentially collect a fee from
anyone who wants to spin-off an

00:33:41.621 --> 00:33:45.133
asset or a debt obligation to
actually rate the soundness of

00:33:45.133 --> 00:33:48.108
the security for whatever it's
supposed to be.

00:33:48.108 --> 00:33:50.920
They sign a rating like Triple
A or Single A.

00:33:50.920 --> 00:33:51.130
Prof: Okay.
 

00:33:51.130 --> 00:33:55.792
And if I'm--Yale was Triple A,
and I think we're now Double A,

00:33:55.792 --> 00:34:00.608
what's a Triple A--what's the
advantage of a Triple A rating?

00:34:00.608 --> 00:34:02.980
Student:
If you have a higher rating

00:34:02.980 --> 00:34:06.028
then that means you can get a
lower cost of capital.

00:34:06.028 --> 00:34:08.782
So, if you actually want to
raise some money you can raise

00:34:08.782 --> 00:34:10.860
it for a lot less--a lower
interest rate.

00:34:10.860 --> 00:34:13.552
Prof: So,
it reduces the cost of capital,

00:34:13.552 --> 00:34:15.960
and it therefore has great
value to you.

00:34:15.960 --> 00:34:21.447
Now, if you could bribe
Moody's, if you were completely

00:34:21.447 --> 00:34:27.344
amoral and you could bribe
Moody's to make something Triple

00:34:27.344 --> 00:34:33.795
A when it was really B,
it would be worth paying a lot,

00:34:33.795 --> 00:34:34.610
right?
 

00:34:34.610 --> 00:34:40.690
The actual economic value of
those ratings is huge.

00:34:40.690 --> 00:34:53.768
What keeps Moody's honest?
 

00:34:53.768 --> 00:34:55.610
Student:
Their reputation;

00:34:55.610 --> 00:34:59.248
the fact that they have,
for years, made sure that the

00:34:59.248 --> 00:35:03.369
ratings that they're giving are
actually safe investments.

00:35:03.369 --> 00:35:04.860
Prof: Okay.
 

00:35:04.860 --> 00:35:08.467
And in general,
people on the buy side are

00:35:08.467 --> 00:35:13.217
going to want the rating
agencies to tell the truth and

00:35:13.217 --> 00:35:18.409
people on the sell side will be
ambivalent about that,

00:35:18.409 --> 00:35:23.030
so there are cross-pressures
there.

00:35:23.030 --> 00:35:29.829
And there is patent evidence of
great inflation in the ratings

00:35:29.829 --> 00:35:32.840
that these firms produce.
 

00:35:32.840 --> 00:35:41.989
Does that surprise you, Paul?
 

00:35:41.989 --> 00:35:42.994
Student:
Not really, no,

00:35:42.994 --> 00:35:45.039
because they get paid by the
sell side not by the buy side.

00:35:45.039 --> 00:35:46.599
Prof: Absolutely.
 

00:35:46.599 --> 00:35:50.978
So, they are doing--they are,
in a sense, appraising as

00:35:50.978 --> 00:35:56.170
instructed and that's a pretty
scary part of this whole thing.

00:35:56.170 --> 00:36:05.760
Let's reach all the way back to
Adam Smith for a minute,

00:36:05.760 --> 00:36:09.929
and Smith's story,
not just of the invisible hand,

00:36:09.929 --> 00:36:14.429
but of the generally benign
working of markets.

00:36:14.429 --> 00:36:21.762
In everything Smith says is
embedded a basic norm of truth

00:36:21.762 --> 00:36:29.610
that I'm not selling you a false
mirage of a loaf of bread;

00:36:29.610 --> 00:36:31.590
I'm selling you an actual loaf
of bread.

00:36:31.590 --> 00:36:37.809
I'm not selling you coffee or a
substance that looks like

00:36:37.809 --> 00:36:40.179
coffee;
I'm selling you coffee.

00:36:40.179 --> 00:36:44.619
And the basic accountability in
bilateral trade,

00:36:44.619 --> 00:36:47.744
where you're buying something
from me or I'm buying something

00:36:47.744 --> 00:36:50.434
from you,
we keep each other honest,

00:36:50.434 --> 00:36:50.989
right?
 

00:36:50.989 --> 00:36:54.635
Where it's two parties and
there's no information

00:36:54.635 --> 00:36:56.079
asymmetry, right?
 

00:36:56.079 --> 00:36:59.340
Where there are two parties
with symmetrical information.

00:36:59.340 --> 00:37:04.172
The most foundational aspect of
a market system is that buyer

00:37:04.172 --> 00:37:08.360
and seller are equipped to keep
each other honest.

00:37:08.360 --> 00:37:12.190
And where there is a huge
information asymmetry,

00:37:12.190 --> 00:37:20.242
we invent things like Moody's
or appraisals of real estate as

00:37:20.242 --> 00:37:24.940
a substitute,
a way of creating or simulating

00:37:24.940 --> 00:37:26.750
information symmetry.
 

00:37:26.750 --> 00:37:35.737
But if the third party agencies
act like sellers to the side

00:37:35.737 --> 00:37:42.286
that pays them,
the information asymmetry is

00:37:42.286 --> 00:37:47.010
actually made worse,
right.

00:37:47.010 --> 00:37:54.478
And the strongest case for
increased government regulation

00:37:54.478 --> 00:38:00.112
of the finance industry
generally, actually,

00:38:00.112 --> 00:38:06.010
is the difficulty of policing
the police;

00:38:06.010 --> 00:38:12.501
of tracking the integrity of
estimates put out there by

00:38:12.501 --> 00:38:19.115
people who are in the business
of correcting information

00:38:19.115 --> 00:38:21.039
asymmetries.
 

00:38:21.039 --> 00:38:32.742
Jaan, are there aspects of the
case that you would urge us to

00:38:32.742 --> 00:38:38.010
pay greater attention to?
 

00:38:38.010 --> 00:38:43.260
Jan Elias:
&gt;

00:38:43.260 --> 00:38:45.682
Well, first of all,
on the Triple A story,

00:38:45.682 --> 00:38:48.045
and this may not be in the
case, per say,

00:38:48.045 --> 00:38:50.469
but it's certainly part of the
thing.

00:38:50.469 --> 00:38:54.280
Not only is there a nice little
boost to the true cost of

00:38:54.280 --> 00:38:56.800
capital if you get rated Triple
A,

00:38:56.800 --> 00:38:59.739
but there are certain funds and
certain buyers,

00:38:59.739 --> 00:39:02.789
like money market funds and
other funds,

00:39:02.789 --> 00:39:04.550
that only can buy Triple
A bonds.

00:39:04.550 --> 00:39:08.311
So once you've crossed that
threshold, you have just

00:39:08.311 --> 00:39:12.219
absolutely increased the number
of people and possible

00:39:12.219 --> 00:39:14.360
purchasers of your funds.
 

00:39:14.360 --> 00:39:16.646
Because if you put money in a
money market fund,

00:39:16.646 --> 00:39:19.079
you want a reasonably liquid
investment, you want a

00:39:19.079 --> 00:39:20.539
reasonably assured return.
 

00:39:20.539 --> 00:39:24.532
These are not supposed to be
risky investments and therefore

00:39:24.532 --> 00:39:27.509
money market funds,
all kinds of other funds,

00:39:27.509 --> 00:39:29.809
are limited to Triple A bonds.
 

00:39:29.809 --> 00:39:34.268
So, getting to the Triple A
level was really important.

00:39:34.268 --> 00:39:36.121
To say something,
you could go,

00:39:36.121 --> 00:39:39.271
"I'm not a big fan of
their performance in this

00:39:39.271 --> 00:39:41.740
case," but in terms of
Moody's &amp;

00:39:41.740 --> 00:39:45.318
Fitch and everything,
the collusion doesn't--there

00:39:45.318 --> 00:39:49.150
doesn't have to be explicit
collusion in the sense that,

00:39:49.150 --> 00:39:53.268
if I give you this bond to
rate, I will never rate a bond

00:39:53.268 --> 00:39:56.579
again unless you give me a
Triple A rating.

00:39:56.579 --> 00:40:00.597
What happened in this case is
Moody's and Fitch and others put

00:40:00.597 --> 00:40:04.353
out fairly explicit guidelines
on what they consider to be

00:40:04.353 --> 00:40:05.210
Triple A.
 

00:40:05.210 --> 00:40:09.536
So, you're the bond packager at
the iBank, you're bringing

00:40:09.536 --> 00:40:11.889
together all these mortgages.
 

00:40:11.889 --> 00:40:15.679
And you say "I have to
reach a fifteen percent

00:40:15.679 --> 00:40:18.630
threshold level,
where it's fifteen percent over

00:40:18.630 --> 00:40:21.822
collateralized,
or I have to buy CDS,

00:40:21.822 --> 00:40:26.601
which are the default swaps,
in order to ensure this

00:40:26.601 --> 00:40:29.708
investment and get it over that
Triple A bump,"

00:40:29.708 --> 00:40:33.730
you do exactly what you need to
do to get that Triple A rating.

00:40:33.730 --> 00:40:37.375
And what happened when the
crisis hit is we had all of

00:40:37.375 --> 00:40:41.501
these people who are just
over the Triple A rating and

00:40:41.501 --> 00:40:44.065
they--
I mean, with them just

00:40:44.065 --> 00:40:47.545
over you don't have a spread--
you don't have a usual

00:40:47.545 --> 00:40:49.289
probability distribution.
 

00:40:49.289 --> 00:40:53.275
All of these guys who were
creating these CDOs knew exactly

00:40:53.275 --> 00:40:56.864
where the finish line was,
and went just a step over that

00:40:56.864 --> 00:40:59.789
to make sure that they would get
the Triple A ratings.

00:40:59.789 --> 00:41:04.670
So, the fact that they were not
very well understood,

00:41:04.670 --> 00:41:08.237
that the historic data went
back three years and they felt

00:41:08.237 --> 00:41:11.869
very confident in doing stuff
with three years of data,

00:41:11.869 --> 00:41:13.960
I think that's an interesting
way.

00:41:13.960 --> 00:41:18.898
Because, when you're looking
for active collusion you expect

00:41:18.898 --> 00:41:24.528
guys in seedy bars,
trading information and dollars

00:41:24.528 --> 00:41:30.260
in brown paper envelopes,
and sometimes it's not that

00:41:30.260 --> 00:41:31.159
explicit.
 

00:41:31.159 --> 00:41:35.652
There are ways that gaming the
system without having anyone do

00:41:35.652 --> 00:41:39.630
anything that even resembles
something that sketchy.

00:41:39.630 --> 00:41:44.797
Prof: So,
it may be that legitimate

00:41:44.797 --> 00:41:51.853
cheating, cheating in a good
blue suit, is more dangerous

00:41:51.853 --> 00:41:58.659
than cheating in a seedier
setting with seedier...

00:41:58.659 --> 00:42:01.311
Jaan Elias:
Or you're using a formula

00:42:01.311 --> 00:42:04.333
that's really untested by a heck
of a lot of data,

00:42:04.333 --> 00:42:06.000
may be also a bad idea.
 

00:42:06.000 --> 00:42:11.760
And to go on,
I'm actually kind of surprised,

00:42:11.760 --> 00:42:15.202
Doug, given that we're at an
elite university with lots of

00:42:15.202 --> 00:42:19.130
people with connections to Wall
Street in some way or another,

00:42:19.130 --> 00:42:23.610
